### Describe the bug

I have an interesting bug with a Blazor Hybrid app that wraps the hls.js library.

My set up is this:

  ` 192.168.0.54                        192.168.1.16`
 `Test media sever>----------------------<Dev Machine`

On the Test media server, I have a Docker httpd:latest container running with _Header set Access-Control-Allow-Origin "*"_ enabled in httpd.conf.  No Firewall.  CORS is not the problem.  It is serving a sample hls video stream on `http://192.168.0.54:8080/video/out.m3u8`

On the dev machine I have another Docker httpd:latest serving up this simple html page straight from hls.js demo:
```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Hls.js demo - basic usage</title>
  </head>

  <body>
    <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/hls.js@1"></script>

    <center>
      <h1>Hls.js demo - basic usage</h1>
      <video height="600" id="video" controls></video>
    </center>

    <script>
      var video = document.getElementById('video');
      if (Hls.isSupported()) {
        var hls = new Hls({
          debug: true,
        });
        hls.loadSource('http://192.168.0.54:8080/video/out.m3u8');
        hls.attachMedia(video);
        hls.on(Hls.Events.MEDIA_ATTACHED, function () {
          video.muted = true;
          video.play();
        });
      }
      // hls.js is not supported on platforms that do not have Media Source Extensions (MSE) enabled.
      // When the browser has built-in HLS support (check using `canPlayType`), we can provide an HLS manifest (i.e. .m3u8 URL) directly to the video element through the `src` property.
      // This is using the built-in support of the plain video element, without using hls.js.
      else if (video.canPlayType('application/vnd.apple.mpegurl')) {
        video.src = 'http://192.168.0.54:8080/video/out.m3u8';
        video.addEventListener('canplay', function () {
          video.play();
        });
      }
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
```

**This simple page works as expected and plays the sample HLS video from the media server**.

Next, I created a Blazor hybrid WinForms app to wrap this code [here ](https://github.com/phollida/HlsWinForm)

Essentially putting the JS in the index.html file (I added Hls Error Events for debugging):
```
<body>
<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/hls.js@1"></script>

<div id="app">Loading...</div>

<div id="blazor-error-ui">
    An unhandled error has occurred.
    <a href="" class="reload">Reload</a>
    <a class="dismiss">🗙</a>
</div>

<script src="_framework/blazor.webview.js"></script>
<script>
    function playVideo(source) {
        var video = document.getElementById('video');
        if (video.canPlayType('application/vnd.apple.mpegurl')) {
            video.src = source;
            video.play();
        } else
        if (Hls.isSupported()) {
            var hls = new Hls({
                debug: true,
            });
            hls.loadSource(source);
            hls.attachMedia(video);

            hls.on(Hls.Events.ERROR, function (event, data) {
                if (data.fatal) {
                    switch (data.type) {
                        case Hls.ErrorTypes.NETWORK_ERROR:
                            // try to recover network error
                            alert('fatal network error encountered, try to recover ' );
                            hls.startLoad();
                            break;
                        case Hls.ErrorTypes.MEDIA_ERROR:
                            alert('fatal media error encountered, try to recover');
                            hls.recoverMediaError();
                            break;
                        default:
                            // cannot recover
                            alert('fatal error encountered, cannot recover');
                            hls.destroy();
                            break;
                    }
                }
            });
            hls.on(Hls.Events.MEDIA_ATTACHED, function () {
                video.muted = true;
                video.play();
            });
        }
    }
</script>
</body>
```

And in the razor page I invoke this function using JSInterop

```
@inject IJSRuntime JSRuntime

<div class="container" style="alignment: center">
    <h1>Hls.js demo - basic usage @source</h1>
    <video height="600" id="video" controls></video>
    <button id="play" @onclick="PlayVideo">Play</button>
</div>

@code {
    string source = "http://192.168.0.54:8080/video/out.m3u8";
    private  void PlayVideo(object? state)
    {
        JSRuntime.InvokeVoidAsync("playVideo",  source);
        StateHasChanged();
    }
}
```

Upon clicking the Play button, HLS throws a NETWORK ERROR without putting a single packet on the wire (confirmed with wireshark), so something is going wrong internally between Blazor and JS.  The JS function is getting the correct source and ID, but it seems like there's a lower level issue that causes JS to throw a Network Error before getting to a HTTP request.  It feels like in internal host not found being thrown or an internal Blazor CORS check that fails for some reason.

It's not a server CORS issue because the HTML based page works fine and I can see the HTTP GET request on the wire.

It's not a firewall issue because I can play the media file no problems with _ffplay_ and _VLC_ form the Dev machine.  Have tried with firewalls off on the dev machine.

### Weird Behavior
This is where it gets weird. 

- If I use any other media address outside my dev LAN the Blazor app works fine.  So if I use the source address of  `https://test-streams.mux.dev/x36xhzz/x36xhzz.m3u8`  the Blazor wrapper will play the stream no problems. 
- If I serve the media files locally from the Dev machine (from the Docker httpd container) the Blazor wrapper works fine - so `http://localhost:8080/video/out.m3u8` and `http://127.0.0.1:8080/video/out.m3u8`work
- If I try and serve the media files from any other address on the LAN I get a NETOWRK ERROR caused by something internal to Blazor and JS.  I have tried a few addresses with the same result.



### Expected Behavior

The Blazor HLS wrapped code should function exactly the same as the HTML code and not only for some cases.

